    "narrative": "The **Austin Waves** offense is anchored today by **Jackson Merrill** (75.27) and **Kyle Tucker** (70.65), both of whom benefit significantly from facing Michael McGreevy. **Jackson Merrill** is our premier play, as his high-leverage leadoff spot against a suspect starter combined with an 87% SB-efficiency tag against a slow-working pitcher creates massive upside in our scarcest category. **Kyle Tucker** remains an elite start, providing stable, high-floor production in the middle of the order. Meanwhile, **Jacob Wilson** (66.11) and **Drake Baldwin** (66.08) round out the top tier; both are currently \"Lineup Pending,\" but should they secure their projected spots at the top of the order, they are locked in as high-efficiency contributors against favorable matchups.\n\nWe are navigating several complex platoon dynamics today. **Gunnar Henderson** (55.17) faces a challenging matchup against Weathers; while his raw talent is immense, the platoon disadvantage depresses his score, though we are capturing extra value through the 100% stolen base frequency expected against this delivery. Conversely, **Josh Lowe** (47.86) carries a higher-than-base projection due to his platoon advantage against Nolan McLean, even if the SP skill metrics suggest a tighter battle. The most difficult decision on the bench was **Coby Mayo** (52.17); while he is a strong prospect, the current depth of our starting corner infield and utility spots\u2014specifically **Josh Jung** (57.60) and **Marcell Ozuna** (56.26)\u2014pushed him to the pine. **Coby Mayo** represents our primary insurance policy should **Josh Jung** or **Vladimir Guerrero Jr.** (58.22) be scratched late.\n\nRisk remains elevated across the board due to the prevalence of \"Lineup Pending\" designations for **Drake Baldwin**, **Nasim Nunez**, **Jacob Wilson**, **Dominic Smith**, **Josh Lowe**, **Andy Pages**, **Jackson Merrill**, and **Kyle Tucker**. While we are modeling for historical spots, any deviation in batting order\u2014specifically for **Jackson Merrill** or **Jacob Wilson** moving out of the leadoff role\u2014will necessitate a re-evaluation of our stolen base targets. **Vladimir Guerrero Jr.** faces the toughest individual matchup of our starters against a 3.34 xERA pitcher; we are counting on his park-adjusted metrics to offset that skill disadvantage. Monitor weather and late scratch reports closely, as our bench depth is optimized specifically for the current projected defensive alignments.",
